The Anguish of Central Banking

this is a sum up of  the book "The Anguish of Central Banking" by Arthur Burns made in the 1970s which feels extremely similar to today.

1 - philosophical and political changes in the US post depression and ww2 caused the inflationary environment




2 - much like the post GFC period, there was a desire for a more interventionist govt policy to help foster employment





3 - but the prosperity of the 60s was not evenly spread and there were substantial societal tensions






4 - these tensions led to an even more interventionist govt.






5 - which became reflexively embedded in societal expectations





6 - the overwhelming goal of policy was full employment




7 - well intentioned environmental policies added to the inflation





8 - entitlements diminished the work ethic of the labor force





9 - the fed had the tools to stop the inflation, but chose not to use them because it had been caught in the social movements of the day





10 - ultimately the fed is beholden to congress, how could it stand in they way of societal changes that congress was attempting to enact?



11 - demographic changes in the workforce made it difficult to understand what the appropiate level of "full employment" was




12 - high inflation made real rates very negative, negating the impact of rate rises



13 - ultimately central banks cant stop politically driven inflation. they have the tools, but not the will




14 - inflation was fed by high voluntary unemployment, deficits, money creation and a high savings rate that was drawn down, making it very difficult to control




15 - all of this led to a conservative political movement that fought back against perceived excessive government intervention




16 - ending the inflationary psychology required drastic therapy.
